Findings¶

In this section I will state the properities of the dataset after the programatic assessment, and if any cleaning is needed before further analysis.

The structure of Ford Gobike-tripdata dataset?¶

  • The data set consists of 183412 entries.
  • There are 16 columns of variable data types
  • Columns' Data types are:

    float64(7), int64(2), object(7)

  • There are 197 missing data in start_station_id, start_station_name, end_station_id, and end_station_name columns.
  • There are 8265 missing data in member_birth_year and member_gender columns.
  • There are no duplicate data.
  • There are 75 different ages of the users involved in the study, 329 start and end stations, 2 user types, 3 gender entries, 4752 trip durations, and 2 conditions of bike share.

Cleaning needed:¶

  1. Making a copy for the dataframe before cleaning, named 'bike'.
  2. Drop the un-necessary rows:
    • Row with NaN values in member_gender and start_station_id columns -Rows with odd values:
      • 'Other' in member_gender column
      • Odd values < 1920 in member_birth_year column
  3. Dropping the unnecessary columns:

    start_station_id, start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_id, end_station_latitude, end_station_longitude, and bike_id.

  4. Reset the index of the bike dataframe.
  5. Convert the type of some columns:
    • start_time and end_time columns from object to date-time
    • member_birth_year column from float to integer
  6. Split the datetime columns into date columns and time columns:
    • start_time column to start_time and start_date columns
    • end_time column to end_time and end_date columns

The structure of the cleaned bike dataset:¶

  • Consistes of 171234 entries and 11 columns.
  • No missing values.
  • Columns data types are:

    int64(2), object(9)

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

  • I'm most interested in figuring out what features are best for predicting the rate and length of bike rides in the tested bike-sharing system.
  • When are most trips taken in terms of time of day, day of the week?
  • How long does the average trip take?
  • Does the above depend on if a user is a subscriber or customer, male or female, bike share for all trip or not?

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • I think that age of the user may play a significant role in the rate of riding biking.

  • Also gender and subscribtion status may affect the choice of taking a bike ride.

  • Additionally, the length or duration of the trip may constitute a factor affecting choice to ride.

Findings of Univariate data visualization¶

  • From the previous univariate exploration, it was abserved that males, subscribers, and those born after 1980 are the most categories used the bike sharing system.

  • Also, the density of biking was observed in working days of the week. Weekends had the least biking activities.

  • In the next step we will look for some relationships between the previous variables.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

  • Age data had unusual years of birth (should be deleted).
  • Duration of trips has a very wide range of values (but are valuable information).
  • Most of trips are for short distances and short time.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

  • The column of member_birth_year had years over 100 years ago which is unlogical and was cleaned to adjust the age to maximum 100 years as a maximum limit.
  • The column of member_gender has a third category called "Other", which was cleaned to adjust the analysis.
  • All "NaN" values was cleaned.

def freq_poly(x, bins = 10, **kwargs):
    """ Custom frequency polygon / line plot code. """
    # set bin edges if none or int specified
    if type(bins) == int:
        bins = np.linspace(x.min(), x.max(), bins+1)
    bin_centers = (bin_edges[1:] + bin_edges[:-1]) / 2

    # compute counts
    data_bins = pd.cut(x, bins, right = False,
                       include_lowest = True)
    counts = x.groupby(data_bins).count()

    # create plot
    plt.errorbar(x = bin_centers, y = counts, **kwargs)

bin_edges = np.arange(60, bike['duration_sec'].max()+1/3, 1/3)
g = sb.FacetGrid(data = bike, hue = 'member_gender', size = 5)

g.add_legend()

  • The relationship between user's year of birth and trip duration is positive because as year of birth is higher, the values of the trip duration are increasing.
  • Most of the trips are short ones. -Violin and Box plots indicated the presence of vast ranges of outliers in trip durations.
  • Most of male and female users are subscribers.
  • Male subscribers with no bike share for all trips are the most users in working days of the month.
  • Most of bike riders were born after 1980, and most of them are males.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

  • Many subscribers born in 90s use bike share system for all trip more than other users.
  • Customers never use bike share system for all trip at all.

Scatter Plot with Shape encoding: Two numeric variables and one categorical variable (Nominal)¶

Scatter plot between year of birth, trip duration, and member gender

# Scatter plot between year of birth, trip duration, and member gender

cat_markers = [['Male', 'o'],
               ['Female', '*']]

    df_cat = bike[bike['member_gender'] == cat]
    plt.scatter(data = df_cat, x = 'member_birth_year', y = 'duration_sec', marker = marker)
plt.legend(['Male','Female'])

plt.xlabel('Year of birth')
plt.ylabel('Trip duration (sec)')
plt.title('Relationship between year of birth, trip duration, and member gender', fontsize=12);
